Natural Language Processing - Twitter Analysis

Problem Statement

Context

Twitter's massive user base of 330 million monthly active users presents a direct avenue for businesses to connect with a broad audience. However, the vast amount of information on the platform makes it challenging for brands to swiftly detect negative social mentions that may impact their reputation. To tackle this, sentiment analysis has become a crucial tool in social media marketing, enabling businesses to monitor emotions in conversations, understand customer sentiments, and gain insights to stay ahead in their industry.

That's why sentiment analysis/classification, which involves monitoring emotions in conversations on social media platforms, has become a key strategy in social media marketing.

Objective

The aim of this project is to build a sentimental analysis model that classify the sentiment of tweets into the positive, neutral & negative.

Data Dictionary

  • tweet_id - A unique identifier for each tweet
  • airline_sentiment - The sentiment label of the tweet, such as positive, negative, or neutral
  • airline_sentiment_confidence - The confidence level associated with the sentiment label
  • negativereason - A category indicating the reason for negative sentiment
  • negativereason_confidence - The confidence level associated with the negative reason
    *airline - The airline associated with the tweet
  • airline_sentiment_gold - Gold standard sentiment label
  • name - The username of the tweet author
  • retweet_count - The number of times the tweet has been retweeted
  • text - The actual text content of the tweet.
  • tweet_coord - Coordinates of the tweet
  • tweet_created - The timestamp when the tweet was created
  • tweet_location - The location mentioned in the tweet
  • user_timezone - The timezone of the tweet author

# Creating function for the barplot for categorical columns.

def cat_barplot(data_frame, column, display_percentage=False):
    total_entries = len(data_frame[column])

    plt.figure(figsize=(len(data_frame[column].unique()) + 2, 6))
    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)

    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data_frame,
        x=column,
        color="skyblue",
        legend=False
    )

    for patch in ax.patches:
        if display_percentage:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * patch.get_height() / total_entries)
        else:
            label = patch.get_height()

        x_position = patch.get_x() + patch.get_width() / 2
        y_position = patch.get_height()

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x_position, y_position),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )

    plt.show()

Using Cross validation to validate the score and to find optimal n_estimators.
In[53]:
range_of_estimator = [50, 100, 150, 200] 
cv_scores = []

for n in range_of_estimator:
    rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n, random_state=42)
    score = cross_val_score(rf_model, X_cv, y_cv, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    cv_scores.append(score.mean())
Plot the misclassification error for each of estimators
In[54]:
cv_err = [1 - accur for accur in cv_scores]
In[55]:
plt.plot(range_of_estimator, cv_err, marker='o', linestyle='-', color='b', label='Misclassification Error')

plt.xlabel("Number of estimator")
plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.title("Misclassification Error vs. Number of estimator")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
In[56]:
optimal_estimator = range_of_estimator[cv_err.index(min(cv_err))]
optimal_estimator
Out[56]:
200
Test the model on testing data

rfc_cv.score(X_test_cv, y_test_cv)

Using Cross validation to validate the score and to find optimal n_estimators
In[69]:
range_of_estimator = [50, 100, 150, 200] 
cv_scores_tf = []

for n in range_of_estimator:
    rf_model_tf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n, random_state=42)
    score = cross_val_score(rf_model_tf, X_tf, y_tf, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    cv_scores_tf.append(score.mean())
Plot the misclassification error for each of estimators
In[70]:
tf_err = [1 - accur for accur in cv_scores_tf]
In[71]:
plt.plot(range_of_estimator, tf_err, marker='o', linestyle='-', color='b', label='Misclassification Error')

plt.ylabel("Misclassification Error")
plt.title("Misclassification Error vs. Number of estimator")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Summary

Conslusion

  • We have created 2 models using CountVectorizer and TfidfVectorizer for doing the sentiment analysis of the tweets.
  • The 2 models that we created we observe that the CountVectorizer method is giving a same accuracy as TfidfVectorizer.
  • With the CountVectorizer method we are getting the score of 79%.
  • With the TfidfVectorizer method we are getting the score of 79%.

Insights

  • The Unities airlines has the most percentage of tweets, followed by US Airways and American airlines. We can also see that Virgin America has the lowest percentage.
  • The percentange of negative tweets is the hightest followed by neutral and then positive.
  • We can observe that the United airline has the highest nuymber of tweets. But in all the airlines the negative tweets are the most. After negative tweets the neutral tweets are the second most and then the positive tweets are the least.
  • The most negative reasons are given to Customer services then followed by late flight and then the next most reason was that the people cannot tell. The damaged lugage and the longliness are the least issue people faced.
  • From the negative cloud image we can observe that the word like delay and customer service is appearing which is the cause of the negative comments and the word united and US Airways has been shown a lot which also confirms with the data that US Airways and united airlines has the most negative comments.

Recommandation

  • We can see that the most number of the tweets are negative in the dataset, So the airlines is not doing well. The airline should see the negative comments and try to reduce the reasons for these negative comments.
  • We can see that the posstibe tweets are very less, so it might be the case that the people who have postive experince with airlines are not giving the feedback. So if this the case then they should try to address this issue too.
  • The United airline has the hishest number of negative tweets, so should give a great focus on decreasing negative reasons here.
  • The most negative reason are of customer service, So there should be a great focus on how the customer service is doing and why they are the negative reason for people. Then the next most negative reasons are of late flight, so this issue should be addressed too. nts.
